Valentine's Day, also known as Saint Valentine's Day, is a holiday celebrated on February 14th each year. The origins of Valentine's Day can be traced back to ancient Roman festivals and Christian traditions.
In ancient Rome, the festival of Lupercalia was held on February 15th to honor the god of fertility, Faunus, and the goddess of love, Venus. During the festival, men would sacrifice a goat and a dog and then whip women with the hides of the animals to promote fertility.
According to Christian tradition, Saint Valentine was a priest who lived in Rome during the 3rd century AD. Emperor Claudius II had outlawed marriage for young men because he believed that single men made better soldiers. Saint Valentine defied the emperor's decree and continued to perform marriages in secret, and as a result, was arrested and executed on February 14th.
During his imprisonment, Saint Valentine is said to have healed the daughter of his jailer and converted her and others to Christianity. Before his execution, he wrote a letter to the jailer's daughter, signing it "From your Valentine," which is where the modern-day expression comes from.
Over time, the holiday evolved to become a day for expressing love and affection, with people exchanging gifts, cards, and messages with their loved ones. Today, Valentine's Day is celebrated in many countries around the world, with the United States being one of the largest celebrants.
